{
  "local_port": 58998,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best ways to cook winkles?",
  "response": "Winkles, also known as whelks, are a type of shellfish that can be enjoyed in several delicious ways. Here are some popular methods for cooking them:\n\n1. **Boiling**:\n   - Start by rinsing the winkles in cold water to clean them.\n   - Bring a pot of salted water to a boil.\n   - Add the winkles and let them boil for about 5\u201310 minutes.\n   - Drain them and serve them warm, often accompanied by vinegar or melted butter for dipping.\n\n2. **Steaming**:\n   - Place the winkles in a steamer basket over boiling water.\n   - Steam for about 5\u201310 minutes until they are cooked through.\n   - Serve with a squeeze of lemon or your favorite dipping sauce.\n\n3. **Grilling**:\n   - Pre-cook the winkles by boiling or steaming them briefly.\n   - Skewer the winkles and brush them with oil, garlic, or your choice of marinade.\n   - Grill for a few minutes until charred and enhanced with smoky flavors.\n\n4. **Baking**:\n   - Preheat the oven to 350\u00b0F (175\u00b0C).\n   - Place the winkles in a baking dish, add a mixture of breadcrumbs, garlic, parsley, and butter on top.\n   - Bake for about 15\u201320 minutes until heated through and slightly crispy on top.\n\n5. **Stir-frying**:\n   - Clean the winkles and briefly boil them.\n   - Stir-fry them in a hot wok with garlic, ginger, soy sauce, and vegetables of your choice.\n   - Cook for a few minutes until everything is heated and well combined.\n\n6. **Adding to Soups or Stews**:\n   - You can add winkles to seafood soups or stews towards the end of cooking. They pair well with flavors like saffron, tomato, and garlic.\n\n7. **Cold Dishes**:\n   - After boiling, winkles can be chilled and served in a salad with citrus dressing or mustard vinaigrette.\n\nRemember that the key to enjoying winkles is ensuring they are fresh and properly cooked, as undercooked shellfish can pose health risks. Enjoy your winkles!",
